<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is Tailwind CSS?", answer: "Tailwind CSS is a utility-first CSS framework that provides low-level utility classes like flex, p-4, text-center, and bg-blue-500. Instead of writing custom CSS, you compose designs directly in your HTML by combining these utility classes. Each class maps to one or a few CSS properties." },
  { question: "Why convert Tailwind to CSS?", answer: "You might need plain CSS when migrating away from Tailwind, when creating email templates that require inline styles, when learning what CSS properties Tailwind classes represent, when working in environments that do not support Tailwind, or when explaining Tailwind to developers unfamiliar with the framework." },
  { question: "Does this tool convert all Tailwind classes?", answer: "This tool converts the most commonly used utility classes including spacing (padding, margin), display, flexbox, grid, typography (font-size, font-weight), borders, border-radius, shadows, opacity, positioning, overflow, cursor, and more. Color classes and responsive prefixes like md: and lg: are noted but not fully expanded." },
  { question: "How does the Tailwind spacing scale work?", answer: "Tailwind uses a numeric scale where each unit equals 0.25rem (4px at default browser settings). So p-1 is padding: 0.25rem, p-4 is padding: 1rem (16px), p-8 is padding: 2rem (32px), and so on. Special values include px (1px), 0.5 (0.125rem), and named values like auto and full (100%)." },
  { question: "What about responsive and state prefixes?", answer: "Responsive prefixes like md:, lg:, and xl: indicate the class applies at that breakpoint and above. State prefixes like hover:, focus:, and dark: apply in specific states. This tool focuses on the base utility conversion. To implement responsive or stateful styles in plain CSS, wrap the properties in the appropriate media query or pseudo-selector." }
]) %>

